Dr. '''Niko Miljanić''' ([[Serbian language|Serbian]] [[Serbian Cyrillic|Cyrillic]]: Нико Миљанић) (1892&ndash;1957) a [[Serbs|Serbian]] [[Anatomy|anatomist]] and [[Surgery|surgeon]], was one of the founders of the [[University of Belgrade School of Medicine|Belgrade Medical School]], which is today part of the [[University of Belgrade]], and has held the first lecture on the newly formed school on December 12, 1920.<ref>[http://afrodita.rcub.bg.ac.rs/~sumc/osnivanjemedfak.htm Osnivanje Medicinskog fakulteta Univerziteta u Beogradu] {{sr icon}}</ref> He has been a full professor of anatomy during the period 1920—1934, then held lectures on surgery [[propaedeutics]] from 1935 until 1947.<ref name="Profile">{{cite journal |vauthors=Lesić A, Draganić-Gajić S, Bumbasirević M |title=[About the professional and ethical profile of an extraordinary physician, humanist and pedagogue, Professor Niko Miljanic] |journal=Srpski Arhiv Za Celokupno Lekarstvo |volume=132 |issue=3-4 |pages=134–7 |year=2004 |pmid=15307318}}</ref> He was relieved from the faculty in 1954. Professor Miljanić was the author of the first textbooks of anatomy in [[Serbian language|Serbian]], a [[monograph]] on [[asepsis]], as well as a lot of scientific articles on anatomy and surgery in different journals in [[Yugoslavia]] and abroad. As a [[France|French]] ex-pupil he was elected president of the French ex-pupils Association and the founder of the bilingual Serbian-French journal ''Anali medicine i hirurgije'' (''Annals of Medicine and Surgery''), published 1927-1934.
In 1930, he unveiled the [[Monument of Gratitude to France]] in Belgrade's [[Kalemegdan|Kalemegdan Park]], together with [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia|King Alexander I of Yugoslavia]]. He fought in both [[Balkan Wars]] and both [[World Wars]]. Miljanić was a member of the French Academy of Surgeons and was decorated with the order of the [[Légion d'honneur]].<ref name="Profile"/>
